<section xml:id="sec-infr_iv" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Type I and Type II errors</title>

 
  <p> 
   <term>Power of a Test:</term> The power of a test is a concept in hypothesis testing. It measures the test's ability to correctly reject a false null hypothesis. 
    It is the probability that the test correctly rejects the 
    null hypothesis <m>(H_o)</m> when a specific alternative hypothesis <m>(H_1)</m> is true. 
  </p>
<p>
  When testing a null hypothesis, <m>(H_o)</m> against alternative hypothesis, <m>(H_1)</m> then there are four possibilities arise
</p>
<p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>(H_o)</m> is accepted when  <m>(H_o)</m> is true. (Correct)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>(H_o)</m> is rejected when  <m>(H_o)</m> is true. (<term>Type I error</term>) or <m>\alpha</m> error.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>\alpha = p (\text{ reject } H_o|H_o \text{ is true}) </m>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>(H_o)</m> is accepted when  <m>(H_o)</m> is false. (<term>Type II error</term>) or <m>\beta</m> error.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>\beta = p (\text{ accept }  H_o|H_1 \text{ is true}) </m>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>(H_o)</m> is rejected when  <m>(H_o)</m> is false. (Correct)
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</p>
</section>